Cumulative strikes around zone

With J.T. Realmuto catching this season, total accumulated strikes are about 0 percent lower than our last season’s model expects. Here are how the differences have accumulated1 this season to date where expected probabilities are binned around the zone2:

Changes colored l have unusually3 low actual strikes, and those colored l have unusually high actual strikes.

Game calls with Pr(strike) above or below average catcher

Umpire: Jim Wolf
Pitcher(s): Ranger Suarez, Hector Neris, Enyel De Los Santos, Jose Alvarado, Archie Bradley, Ian Kennedy

In our Monday game against the Washington Nationals, our catcher faced 78 unique strike zones in Phillies’s called pitches, with 52 balls ◇ and 26 strikes ○4, shown below in A, from the pitcher’s viewpoint. The fill gradient reflects our last season model’s difference in strike probability between J.T. Realmuto and an average catcher5. These zones vary — vertically and horizontally — by more than two baseball widths from pitch to pitch as game factors6 change.

Importantly, the zones shown in A represent where we expect an umpire to call a strike half the time, a ball the other half. As the ball moves further from those lines, our expectations of the umpire call change. In B, for the first called pitch, we show a range [0.1, 0.9]7 of called-strike probabilities:

Explorable differences between umpire calls and modeled probabilities of strikes

Below, we can explore the percentage difference between the umpire calls and modeled probabilities of those calls, with corresponding video footage. Circles ○ in the top row represent called pitches (ball, strike) and lightness of the color represent how close8 our modeled strike probability was to the actual call {0, 1} for each handedness (throw-stand) matchup {LL,LR,RL,RR}.

Of note, the graphics below only show pitches where the differences of called ball or strike from modeled probatility of strikes exceed ± 0.10.

Circles ○ in the bottom row represent the corresponding estimate of runs saved from that variation.

Hovering a pointer over a circle ○ links ○—○ pitches in top and bottom rows, and provides more details of the play in a tooltip. Clicking a pitch loads its game video:
